
Main commands: 
git clone <link>  (this command will clone a repository on github in our local machine)
git remote add origin <link> (this command will set a repo on git hub as our destination for the project on our local machine)
git init <to initialize a folder so that git tracks it>
git add . (adds all files and folders and stages for commit)
git commit -m "message"  (commits the project and changes done, saves , takes a snapshot)
git branch -m main (goes to the main branch)
git push origin main (push last commit to the main branch)
git pull origin main (pulls the main branch from github to local machine)
git remote -v (to check the name of the remote repo)


Branch Commands : 
git branch (check what branch you are currently on ?)
git branch -m <newname> (to rename a branch)
git checkout <branchname> (to change branch name)
git checkout -b <newbranch> (to create a new branch)
git branch -d <branchname> (to delete a branch)
git push origin <branchname> (to push to a specific branch)
git diff <branchname> (compares the diffrences between branch which i am on and <branchname>)
git merge <branchname> (merge branch with <branchname>)
A branch can also be merged through a pull request from github
conflicts can be resolved manually between brances (accept incoming, accept existing, accespt both)

undoing changes: 
case 1 : stages changes
git reset <filename> or git reset (for one file or all files)
case 2 : commited change
git reset head~1  (moves back to status before last git add)
git log (shows all git commits)
git reset <hashcode> (if i want to move back before multiple git adds )
git reset --hard <hashcode> (undo changes from commit and vs code too)

